---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import SeeAlso from "../../components/SeeAlso.astro";
import CollapsibleSection from "../../components/CollapsibleSection.astro";
import IdentityGenerator from "../../components/IdentityGenerator";
import Quiz from "../../components/Quiz";
import { getQuiz } from "../../data/quizzes";
import { NODE_ADDR_BYTES, PUBKEY_BYTES } from "../../lib/constants";
---

<Base title="Identity">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <p class="text-fips-accent font-mono text-sm mb-2">Lesson 2</p>
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Identity</h1>

    <section class="space-y-4 text-fips-text leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Most networks separate identity from addressing. You get an IP address from a DHCP server,
        and separately prove who you are through certificates issued by a third party. FIPS
        collapses these into a single step: your cryptographic keypair <em>is</em> your address.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">The keypair</h2>

      <p>
        A FIPS node starts by generating (or loading) a secp256k1 keypair. This is the same elliptic
        curve used by Bitcoin and Nostr. The private key stays on your node. The public key, encoded
        in bech32 as an <code class="mono text-fips-accent">npub</code>, is how other users and
        applications identify you.
      </p>

      <p>
        From this single public key, FIPS derives two more identifiers. Both are deterministic. No
        coordination with anyone else is needed.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">The derivation pipeline</h2>

      <div
        class="rounded-lg border border-fips-border p-4 bg-fips-surface/30 font-mono text-sm space-y-2"
      >
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <span class="text-fips-muted w-32">Public Key</span>
          <span class="text-fips-text">({PUBKEY_BYTES} bytes, compressed secp256k1)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="text-fips-accent pl-4">↓ bech32 encode x-only key</div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <span class="text-fips-muted w-32">npub</span>
          <span class="text-fips-text">Application identity. What you share with others.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="text-fips-accent pl-4">
          ↓ SHA-256, truncate to {NODE_ADDR_BYTES} bytes
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <span class="text-fips-muted w-32">node_addr</span>
          <span class="text-fips-text">Routing identifier. Appears in packet headers.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="text-fips-accent pl-4">↓ prepend 0xfd to first 15 bytes</div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <span class="text-fips-muted w-32">IPv6 address</span>
          <span class="text-fips-text">fd00::/8 ULA for legacy IPv6 apps.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The node_addr is a one-way hash. Given a node_addr, you cannot recover the public key. This
        is the property that protects identity at the routing layer: intermediate routers see
        node_addrs in packet headers but cannot determine which npub (which person) the traffic
        belongs to. An observer who already knows your npub can check whether a particular node_addr
        is yours, but they cannot enumerate identities from traffic alone.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Try it yourself</h2>

      <p>
        The widget below generates a real secp256k1 keypair in your browser and walks through the
        derivation. Each step produces a different representation of the same identity.
      </p>

      <IdentityGenerator client:visible />

      <CollapsibleSection title="Who sees what?">
        <p>
          Different actors in the network have access to different levels of identity information.
          This table summarizes what each can observe:
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-4">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-fips-border text-left">
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 text-fips-muted font-medium">Observer</th>
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 text-fips-muted font-medium">Sees</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-fips-text">
              <tr class="border-b border-fips-border/50">
                <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Transport observer</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-fips-muted"
                  >Encrypted packets, timing, packet sizes. No FIPS-level identifiers.</td
                >
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-fips-border/50">
                <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Direct peer</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-fips-muted"
                  >Your npub (from Noise IK handshake), traffic volume, timing.</td
                >
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-fips-border/50">
                <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Intermediate router</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-fips-muted"
                  >Source and destination node_addrs, packet size. Cannot read payload.</td
                >
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Destination</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-fips-muted"
                  >Your npub (from Noise XK session), payload content.</td
                >
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </CollapsibleSection>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Why Nostr keys?</h2>

      <p>
        FIPS could have defined its own key format. Instead, it reuses the Nostr cryptographic
        stack: secp256k1 for keys, Schnorr signatures for authentication, SHA-256 for hashing,
        ChaCha20-Poly1305 for AEAD. This means an existing Nostr identity can serve as a FIPS node
        identity without generating anything new.
      </p>

      <p>
        Key rotation is straightforward but destructive: a new keypair produces a new node_addr and
        IPv6 address. All existing sessions must be re-established. There is no mechanism (yet) for
        announcing a successor key.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Quiz client:visible questions={getQuiz("2-identity")} title="Identity Quiz" />

    <SeeAlso terms={["npub", "node_addr", "ipv6-ula"]} />
    <LessonNav current={2} />
  </article>
</Base>
